<!-- The document content area with serialized nodes -->

<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>Claims Direct<Node id="13"/>, the <Node id="19"/>UK<Node id="21"/> personal injury specialist, on <Node id="53"/>Friday<Node id="59"/> reluctantly agreed to recommend a <Node id="94"/>£19.4m<Node id="101"/> (<Node id="103"/>$27.5m<Node id="109"/>) bid from its two founders which only <Node id="148"/>last month<Node id="158"/> it condemned as &quot;opportunistic&quot; and &quot;cynical&quot;.<Node id="205"/>

<Node id="207"/>The company, which is facing a probe from the <Node id="253"/>Department of Trade and Industry<Node id="285"/>, has seen its shares slide from <Node id="318"/>353½p<Node id="324"/>, valuing it at <Node id="340"/>£681m<Node id="346"/> <Node id="347"/>last September<Node id="361"/>, to as low as <Node id="376"/>5p<Node id="378"/> <Node id="379"/>this year<Node id="388"/>.<Node id="389"/>

<Node id="391"/>And the recommendation is likely to anger some shareholders as the <Node id="458"/>10p<Node id="461"/> offer is a <Node id="473"/>95 per cent<Node id="484"/> discount to the company&apos;s flotation price of <Node id="530"/>180p<Node id="534"/> per share. In <Node id="549"/>early Friday<Node id="561"/> trading the shares dropped by <Node id="592"/>1¾p<Node id="596"/> to <Node id="600"/>9½p<Node id="604"/>.<Node id="605"/>

<Node id="607"/>Claims Direct<Node id="620"/> said it had been left with no alternative but to recommend the offer made by <Node id="698"/>Tony Sullman<Node id="710"/> and <Node id="715"/>Colin Poole<Node id="726"/>, who own <Node id="736"/>43 per cent<Node id="747"/> of the company.<Node id="763"/>

<Node id="765"/>The two men had been talking to private investor <Node id="814"/>Simon Ware-Lane<Node id="829"/> who was interested in buying part of their stake, in a move which would see <Node id="906"/>Mr Sullman<Node id="916"/> and <Node id="921"/>Mr Poole<Node id="929"/> resign from the board.<Node id="952"/>

<Node id="954"/>However, on <Node id="966"/>Friday<Node id="972"/> they refused to extend the deadline for their offer which closes on <Node id="1041"/>Monday<Node id="1047"/>, despite pleas from the board.<Node id="1078"/>

<Node id="1080"/>Claims Direct<Node id="1093"/>&apos;s independent directors said in view of the uncertainty about the talks and with no guarantee that <Node id="1193"/>Mr Poole<Node id="1201"/> and <Node id="1206"/>Mr Sullman<Node id="1216"/> will extend their offer, they were forced to recommend the bid.<Node id="1280"/>

<Node id="1282"/>&quot;We recognise that the change in recommendation will come as a bitter blow to all those who have indicated their willingness to tackle the various problems that have plagued the company over the past months,&quot; the independent directors said in a statement.<Node id="1537"/>

<Node id="1539"/>Mr Sullman<Node id="1549"/> and <Node id="1554"/>Mr Poole<Node id="1562"/> will pay <Node id="1572"/>£11.1m<Node id="1579"/> for the outstanding shares they do not own to take the business private. This is little more than the net cash left in the business.<Node id="1712"/>

<Node id="1714"/>&quot;It wouldn&apos;t surprise me if some shareholders just reject the offer anyway because they have been so unhappy with <Node id="1828"/>Sullman<Node id="1835"/> and <Node id="1840"/>Poole<Node id="1845"/>,&quot; said one analyst.<Node id="1865"/>

<Node id="1867"/>After the refusal to extend the offer, <Node id="1906"/>Claims Direct<Node id="1919"/> was left with little option but to accept.<Node id="1962"/>

<Node id="1964"/>Its attempts at a defence were hampered by revelations of the <Node id="2026"/>DTI<Node id="2029"/> probe. The company was also not helped by the <Node id="2076"/>UK High Court<Node id="2089"/>, which failed to give clear guidance <Node id="2127"/>last week<Node id="2136"/> on levels of premiums that companies like <Node id="2179"/>Claims Direct<Node id="2192"/> can charge.<Node id="2204"/>

<Node id="2206"/>Claims Direct<Node id="2219"/> requires customers to take out an insurance policy before it pursues compensation claims on their behalf. This practice has been attacked, with the company accused of charging unreasonable premiums.<Node id="2418"/>

<Node id="2420"/>Attacks by the press earlier <Node id="2449"/>this year<Node id="2458"/> hit trading, leading to two profits warnings.<Node id="2504"/>

<Node id="2506"/>The bad publicity saw a severe drop in the number of claimants using <Node id="2575"/>Claims Direct<Node id="2588"/>, and accepted cases dropped from 4,000 a month to 1,000 in <Node id="2648"/>June<Node id="2652"/> despite a <Node id="2663"/>£17m<Node id="2668"/> advertising campaign.<Node id="2690"/></TextWithNodes>
